1. Introduction

The creation of common enemies in votersâ imaginary seems to be a trending strategy used by presidential candidates worldwide. George W. Bushâs âwar on terrorâ in 2004 and Trumpâs politicization of everything in 2016 and anti-Chinaâs campaign in 2020 are some examples of fear-oriented campaigns deployed by presidential candidates to influence votersâ behavior in the U.S. In Latin America, candidates also use fear-mongering strategies, especially to spread fear around the âcommunist threatâ supposedly represented by leftist candidates. Bolsonaroâs 2018 and 2022âs campaigns, for instance, brought âcommunismâ and socialismâ to the fore in Brazil. Intoning âBrazil cannot become a new Venezuelaâ, he connected the now president-elect Lula da Silva to Nicolas Maduroâs regime in Venezuela and fueled votersâ fear about an external communist threat during the last Brazilian General elections. In Colombia, the first-ever leftist president Gustavo Petro was also a target of an anti-communism fear mongering campaign perpetrated by his opponents during the last Colombian General Elections. Similarly, in Chile, the leftist and now president Gabriel Boric had to deal with several fear mongering strategies around his candidature and a âcommunist threatâ deployed by his right-ring opponent Jose Antonio Kast during the last Chilean General Elections in December of 2021.

The heavenly use of anti-communism and anti-socialism fear-oriented campaigns in Latin America might negatively impact leftistsâ vote share by associating their candidatures with a false communist threat. To further evaluate this question, this paper explores the use of anti-communist fear-mongering strategies during electoral campaigns in Latin America. More specifically, it examines the effect of targeting leftist candidates as âsocialistsâ or âcommunistsâ or associating them with âVenezuelaâ on their subsequent vote share. We focus on the recent elections in Chile, Colombia, and Brazil and in the victory of the leftists Boric, Petro, and Lula, respectively. All three candidates won their presidential elections amid an intense fear-oriented campaign around the âcommunist threatâ perpetrated by their opponents. This paper examines whether deploying fear-mongering campaigns around a communism threat harms leftist candidatesâ state-level vote share (Borba 2021; Chagas, Modesto, and MagalhÃ£es 2019; Purdum, n.d.; Rhodes and Vayo 2019)

To conduct the analysis, we use data from Google Trends to measure peopleâs searches for the words âVenezuelaâ, âCommunismâ, and âSocialismâ three months before the runoff elections in Brazil, Colombia, and Chile. We look for the intensity of the searches (i.e., number of hits) and the interest by region (i.e., the states with the most number of hits). We then match the Google Trends data with electoral data containing leftistsâ vote share to assess the effect of anti-communist fear-mongering strategies on the electoral outcomes. We hypothesize that (i) people will search âVenezuelaâ, âComunismoâ, and âSocialismoâ more as we get closer to election day; and (ii) that leftists candidates will have a lower vote share in states where the communist-related words had the most hits in Brazil, Colombia, and Chile.

2. Data

We used the âgtrendsâ package in R to obtain the data on the searches for communism-related words three months prior to the elections in Brazil, Colombia, and Chile. We used âcommunismâ, âsocialismâ, and âVenezuelaâ as the key words and change the geographic location and the time frame for each of the countries. For Brazil, we set the time frame from July to October of 2022, as the runoff of the Brazilian elections took place on October 31st, 2022. For Colombia, we set the time frame from March to May of 2022, as the runoff of the Colombian elections took place on June 19th, 2022. Finally, for Chile, we set the time frame from September to December of 2021, as the runoff of the Chilean elections took place on December 19th, 2021. We obtained different data on the searches using the command names(), including interest over time, interest by country, interest by city, interest by region, and related topics. In this paper, we only focus on interest over time and interest by region.

After getting information on the overall searches, we disagregated the data to get the search hits by each countryâs states. We did this by creating a new object containing only the âinterest by regionâ column from the main data set. This new object gives us the search hits for âcommunismâ, âsocialismâ, and âVenezuelaâ for all countries by states. The âhead()â command shows the 6 states with the most hits for each country.

Our last step was to obtain electoral data from the last elections for each country. We did this by collecting the vote share data from each countryâs public available electoral organizations. For Brazil, we accessed the data at the Brazilian Superior Electoral Tribunal website (âhttps://resultados.tse.jus.br/oficial/app/index.html#/m/onboardingâ) where they had the vote share for all candidates for the first and second rounds disagreggated by states. For Colombia, we collected the electoral data from the RegistradurÃ­a Nacional del Estado Civil (âhttps://www.registraduria.gov.co/â) and for Chile at the Servicio Electoral de Chile website (âhttps://www.servel.cl/â). Finally, we merged data from all the countries and the search hits from Google Trends to create a data set with all the main variables. We used this to run the regression and assess our hypothesis.

All data used is available at https://github.com/juangelvezf/Google-trends-and-communism.

# Getting data on the searches, 3 months before run-off
br <- gtrends(c("comunismo", "socialismo","venezuela"), geo = "BR", time = "2022-07-31 2022-10-31", low_search_volume = TRUE)  #Brazil
col <- gtrends(c("comunismo", "socialismo"), geo = "CO", time = "2022-03-20 2022-06-20", low_search_volume = TRUE)  #Colombia, no Venezuela
col1 <- gtrends(c("comunismo", "socialismo","venezuela"), geo = "CO", time = "2022-03-20 2022-06-20", low_search_volume = TRUE) #Colombia, with Venezuela
ch0 <- gtrends(c("comunismo", "socialismo"), geo = "CL", time = "2021-09-19 2021-12-19", low_search_volume = TRUE) #Chile, no Venezuela
ch <- gtrends(c("comunismo", "socialismo","venezuela"), geo = "CL", time = "2021-09-19 2021-12-19", low_search_volume = TRUE) #Chile, with Venezuela

3. Results

In this section, we present our data exploration and main results. We start by explaining how we explored the data using Google Trends and then we present our main findings from the OLS regression models.

3.1 Data exploration

Before running the models to test our hypotheses, we explored our data by looking at the relationship between proximity to election day and searching for communist-related words using Google Trends data. We then disaggregated the data by state to see where the search hits were stronger.

The search hits plots are shown below. We added âVenezuelaâ, âComunismoâ, and âSocialismoâ for all countries, but the first word was just significant enough to plot in the Brazilian case. As the graph shows, in all the countries, there is a positive relationship between proximity to election day and search for communism-related words on Google. In Brazil, âVenezuelaâ seems to be the most searched word, followed by âComunismoâ, and âSocialismoâ. In Colombia, âSocialismoâ was the word with the most searches close to elections day. In Chile, âComunismoâ remained relatively constant as the most searched word three months before the elections.

3.2 Analysis

We raise two main hypotheses in this paper. First, we hypothesize that the search hits for âVenezuelaâ, âComunismoâ, and âSocialismoâ will increase as we get closer to electionsâ day in Brazil, Chile, and Colombia. Second, we expect that left-wing candidates will have a lower vote-share where the search hits for these words are higher. To test our theory, we run two OLS models.

The first model takes the search for the three words as the dependent variable and the proximity to the election day as the main independent variable. This latter ranges from -90 to 0 days before elections. We also included country-fixed effects, with Brazil being the excluded category. The model output is shown below. Our results suggest that proximity to election day is positively associated with Google searches for communism-related words. One unit increase in the days before the election variable leads to an increase in the search for âVenezuelaâ, âComunismoâ and âSocialismo by 0.056 points, 0.164 points, 0.071 points, respectively, on average, holding all else constant.

The plot below shows that Brazil was the only country where Venezuela seemed to be a significant word. This explains why Chile and Colombia have both statistically significant but negative coefficients for the search of âVenezuelaâ in comparison to Brazil. One unit change in the days before the election variable leads to a decrease in the search for âVenezuelaâ by 13.4 and 10.06 points in Chile and Colombia, respectively, compared to Brazil. On the other hand, the constant term, which in this case represents Brazil on election day (0 days before the election), tells us that on election day the search for âVenezuelaâ increased by 23.8 points in the country, on average. For the âComunismoâ search, all the coefficients are statistically significant, with the one for Colombia being the only negative. On overage, one unit change in the days before the election variable leads to an increase in the search for âComunismoâ by 8.9 points in Chile and to a decrease by 12.4 points in Colombia compared to Brazil. In this latter on election day, the search for âComunismoâ increased by 20.7 points. Lastly, for the âSocialismoâ search, the coefficient for Colombia and the constant are the only ones statistically significant, yet only the latter is positive. On average, one unit change in the days before the election variable leads to a decrease in the search for âSocialismoâ by 8.7 points in Colombia compared to Brazil. In this latter on election day, nevertheless, the search for âSocialismoâ increased by 12.9 points, on average.

The regression results and the correlation plot for the second hypothesis are shown below. The dependent variable is the vote share at the state-level in the run-off for the three left-wing candidates in Brazil, Chile, and Colombia. The independent variable are the Google searches for the three words (Venezuela, Socialismo, and Comunismo). We focus only on the run-off because (i) third parties usually have a significant effect on vote shares in the first round and (ii) abstention is lower in the second round. We also included country-fixed effects, with Brazil being the excluded category. Our results suggest that searches for Venezuela are negatively and significantly correlated with left-wing party vote share in the second round, on average, holding all else constant. One unit increase in the search for âVenezuelaâ decreases vote share for left-wing candidates by 0.314 points. Searches for âComunismoâ and âSocialismoâ do not have a significant relationship with the left-wing candidatesâ vote share. The correlation plot shows the negative relationship between Venezuela search hits and leftistsâ vote share in the second round, as predicted from our model.

4. Discussion

In sum, our results suggest that the use of anti-communism fear-oriented campaigns in Latin America has a negative effect on left-wing candidatesâ vote share when it is framed around Venezuela. More specifically, it seems that associating leftists with Venezuela harms these candidatesâ electoral outcomes, thus being an effective strategy for their opponents. We found that people search relatively more for communism-related words as we get closer to election day, which points to the existence and salience of fear-mongering campaigns. Additionally, we found that only the search for Venezuela is negatively associated with leftist candidatesâ vote share. Our results also suggest that in Brazil the effects were significantly higher than in other countries for all communist-related words.

We need to address three issues for our results to be sustained. One is related to how information spreads and when people decide to search for anti-communist words. The data show that people are more likely to use this search string late in the election campaign when people are less informed and information is confusing. Our results stand on solid ground here as people continue to search for these words as the political campaign evolves. Yet we should further research the âlifespanâ of some terms related to their ability to survey populations, considering that their use might drop as information gets more transparent and people become more informed. Second, our choice to use data at the state level may raise questions regarding whether national or city-level data matter. People inform themselves in the federal and local news and use that information, so it would be interesting to analyze city-level data as well. Lastly, people could search our three main words because they have a left-wing political affiliation. While plausible, we do not believe this could be driving our results. Communist and socialist parties got less than 10% of the vote share in the congress elections in each country, so it is not a majority. In any case, we would have to control for that to make sure our model does not suffer from endogeneity.
